   Last year a biography of Mrs Norma Major - or, if we are being old-fashioned, Mrs John Major - claimed that the Majors' favourite film was Being There.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   Yet when I heard about this, my mind immediately went back to an incident a few months ago, when Major visited Pittsburgh, centre of the US steel industry, as part of his American tour.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Major's father, and therefore by extension John Major himself, can be all things to all people.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   No, Major's technique is very much his own invention, very much a reflection of his own particular character, itself a product of his unsettled family background.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   Dominic Lawson is editor of The Spectator
  </a>
